text: Title: Characterization of a Membrane-bound O-Acetyltransferase Involved in  Trioxacarcin Biosynthesis Offers Insight into Its Catalytic Mechanism Authors: Yue Yin, Yi Shen, Song Meng, Mei Zhang, Hai-Xue Pan, and Gong-Li Tang* This manuscript has been accepted and appears as an Accepted Article online. This work may now be cited as: Chin. J. Chem. 2020, 38, 10.1002/cjoc.202000284. The final Version of Record (VoR) of it with formal page numbers will soon be published online in Early View: http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/cjoc.202000284. ISSN 1001-604X • CN 31-1547/O6 mc.manuscriptcentral.com/cjoc www.cjc.wiley-vch.de Summary of main observation and conclusion:    Trioxacarcin A (TXN-A) is a polycyclic aromatic natural product with remarkable biological activity. TxnB11,  a membrane-bound O-acetyltransferase involved in TXN-A biosynthesis that is difficult for protein manipulation, is biochemically characterized here for its  acetylation function on C4-sugar. A proposed catalytic mechanism is supported by transmembrane helix analysis and site-directed mutagenesis, in which  four conserved amino acid residues His35, Ser71, His100 and His317 are essential for enzyme activity. We tested the substrate tolerance of TxnB11 to acyl  donors in vitro and found that TxnB11 can also utilize propionyl-CoA and glycolyl-CoA, resulting in two new TXN analogs with anti-tumor activity. This work  provides a first understanding of the catalytic mechanism of this unusual acyltransferase family and presents good candidates for creating structural diversity  for natural products.  Characterization of a Membrane-bound O-Acetyltransferase Involved in  Trioxacarcin Biosynthesis Offers Insight into Its Catalytic Mechanism  Yue Yin,a Yi Shen,a Song Meng,a Mei Zhang,a Hai-Xue Pan,a,b and Gong-Li Tanga,b,*

aState Key Laboratory of Bioorganic and Natural Products Chemistry, Center for Excellence in Molecular Synthesis, Shanghai Institute of Organic Chemistry,  University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 345 Lingling Road, Shanghai 200032, China  bSchool  of  Chemistry  and  Material  Sciences, Hangzhou  Institute  for  Advanced  Study,  University  of  Chinese  Academy  of  Sciences,  1  Sub-lane  Xiangshan,  Hangzhou 310024, China. DOI: 10.1002/cjoc.202000XXX  Background and Originality Content  Trioxacarcin A (TXN-A, 1, Figure 1), an anti-tumor compound of  the  anthracycline  family,  was  first  isolated  from  Streptomyces  bottropensis  NRRL  12051  in  1981.[1]  Later  in  2004,  more  TXN-A  analogs  were  discovered  from  a  marine-derived  actinomycete,  Streptomyces sp. B8652.[2] TXN-A contains a complex ring system  with a spiro-epoxide moiety and two attached sugars. Significantly,  it has been reported that the compound possesses extraordinary  anti-tumor activity with subnanomolar IC70 values against various  cancer  cells,  and  exhibits  high  potent  anti-bacterial  and  anti- malarial activity.[1,2] The notable biological activity of TXN-A is due  to its tight interaction with DNA. Txn-A binds DNA by positioning  the C4-sugar in the minor groove and the C13-sugar in the major  groove,  meanwhile  the  epoxide  moiety  binds  covalently  to  the  guanine N7, followed by cleavage of DNA strand.[3]

The remarkable anti-cancer activity and the unusual chemical  structure of TXN-A have continuously aroused wide attention in its  chemical  synthesis  and  biosynthesis.  Our  group  has  cloned  the  biosynthetic gene cluster of TXN-A,[4] which contains a gene txnB11  encoding  a  hypothetical  O-acetyltransferase.  Inactivation  of  txnB11  leads  to  the  interruption  of  TXN-A  biosynthesis  and  produces TXN-D, an analog of TXN-A lacking the O-acetyl group on  C4-sugar (2, Figure 1). Compared with TXN-A, 2 is approximately 10  times  less active, which conﬁrms the importance of the O-acetyl  moiety for the anti-tumor activity of TXNs.[5]  Although the previous gene knockout experiments suggested  that  TxnB11  could  be  an  O-acetyltransferase,  it  still  lacks  direct  biochemical  evidence.  TxnB11  shows  moderate  sequence  similarity  to  putative  acyltransferases  such  as  CmmA,[6]  TcaM,[7]  MegY,[8]  MppN,[9]  MppM,[9]  Srm6,[10]  Azi15,[11]  etc.  which  are  involved in the biosynthesis of various natural products showed in  Figure  1,  respectively. Herein,  we  describe  this  O- in  vitro,  and  propose  a  possible  catalytic  acetyltransferase  mechanism. Furthermore, we attempt to change the acyl group on  C-4 of TXN-A, using the TxnB11-catalyzed reaction, to expand the  extent and diversity of this class of highly active natural products.  中 国 化 学 - An International Journal Figure 1    Chemical structures of trioxacarcins and other natural products  bearing  acylated  group  putatively  catalyzed  by  membrane-bound  O- acetyltransferases.  The  acyl  moieties  are  highlighted  with  circles.  The  putative acyltransferases involved are annotated.  Localization and in vitro assay of TxnB11

For  biochemical  assay  of  the  in  vitro  activity  of  TxnB11,  the  TxnB11-coding gene was amplified and cloned into the expression  vector  pGEX4T-1,  which  encodes  an  N-terminal  GST-tag.  The  constructed plasmid was transferred into Escherichia coli and the  corresponding  protein  was  overexpressed.  The  E.  coli  cells  were  collected,  resuspended,  and  disrupted  by  sonication.  Cell  debris  was removed by low-speed centrifugation. Samples were collected  from  the  resultant  supernatant  and  named  ‘whole-cell  extracts’.  The supernatant was further  ultra-centrifuged at 100,000 g for 1  hour  then  the  cell  membranes  were  pelleted.  The  resulting  supernatant  was  designated  ‘soluble  fraction’.  The  membrane  fraction was solubilized in Tris-HCl buffer containing 1% n-dodecyl- β-D-maltopyranoside  (DDM)  or  Triton  X-100,  that  was  named  ‘membrane fraction’. The empty vector pGEX-4T-1 was served as a  negative  control.  All  the  fractions  were  analyzed  by  Western  blotting  using  anti-GST  antibody.  The  expression  of  GST-tagged  TxnB11 was detected in all three fractions (Figure 2A). All rights reserved. activity. Purified TXN-D (2) was used as the acetyl acceptor,[5] and  the commercially available acetyl-CoA was chosen as the acyl donor.  HPLC  analysis  of  the  enzymatic  reactions  showed  that  TxnB11  catalyzed the regioselective acetylation of TXN-D (2) to TXN-A (1) in  the presence of acetyl-CoA. In the membrane fraction solubilized  in DDM, the substrate 2 could be almost completely converted to  TXN-A.  However,  a  trace  of  the  product  was  determined  in  the  whole-cell  extracts  and  soluble  fraction  (Figure  2B).  Besides,  the  reaction efficiency in DDM was much higher than that in Triton X- 100.  DDM  is  considered  to  be  more  efficient  in  preserving  the  activity of membrane proteins than other detergents due to its high  critical micelle concentration (CMC).[12] These results demonstrate  that  TxnB11  is  a  membrane-bound  O-acetyltransferase,  which  is  consistent with the idea that acetylation of C4-sugar is one of the  latest biosynthesis steps in the biosynthesis of TXN-A, taking place  in close relation to its secretion.

Lane 1, molecular weight marker. B, HPLC analysis of the in vitro  acetylation of TXN-D (2) to TXN-A (1) catalyzed by GST control (I), whole- cell extracts (II), soluble fraction (III), membrane fraction in Triton X-100 (IV)  and membrane fraction in DDM (V), with pure TXN-A as a standard (VI).  Proposed catalytic mechanism of TxnB11  Next, we sought to explore the catalytic mechanism of TxnB11  since the mode of action of this acetyltransferase family had never  been  reported.  Multiple  sequence  alignment  of  TxnB11  and  its  homologs  mentioned  above  revealed  all  conserved  motifs  and  amino  acid  residues.  Among  these,  there  were  nine  highly  conserved residues containing functional side chains as hydroxyl,  sulfhydryl, or amino group (Figure 3). The functional structure and  Chin. J. Chem. 2018, XX, 1－X  conservation of these residues suggest that they may be involved  in the enzyme activity.  Figure 3    Multiple sequence alignment of TxnB11 and its analogs. Amino  acid  sequences  were  obtained  from  GenBank.  Nine  highly  conserved  residues containing the functional side chains are showed with arrows.

Nine  mutants  were  prepared  via  site-directed  mutagenesis  utilizing  overlap  PCR  method,  and  the  mutated  genes  were  confirmed  by  sequence  analysis.  The  constructed  mutant  genes  were ligated with the vector pGEX-4T-1. The mutant and wild-type  (WT)  proteins  were  overproduced  in  E.  coli  and  the  membrane  fractions  were  isolated  using  the  method  described  above.  The  quantitation  of  proteins  was  performed  by  Western  blotting  (Figure S1). Then, the catalytic activity of the mutant enzymes was  measured with WT TxnB11 as a control. As shown in Figure 4A, five  mutant enzymes displayed similar activity with WT. On the contrast,  when residues His35, Ser71, His100 and His317 were replaced by  Alanine,  the  activity  of  the  enzyme  was  significantly  reduced,  suggesting  that  these  four  residues  were  critical  for  the  acetyltransferase activity. The mutant H35A even completely lost  activity. It is widely accepted that the transfer reactions catalyzed  by  acyltransferases  involve  two  half-reactions,  similar  to  the  mechanism of serine proteases. As the first step in the reaction, a  catalytic  serine  of  the  enzyme  attacks  the  thioester  carbonyl  of  acyl-CoA,  releasing  CoA  and  forming  the  acyl-enzyme  complex.  Chin. J. The amino acid sequence of TxnB11 was analyzed to predict its  transmembrane  helices  by  (Protein  Homology/analogy Recognition Engine V2.0).[13] The beginning and  stop  of  each  transmembrane  helix  illustrated  with  a  number  representing the residue index (Figure 4B). Three of the residues  important to catalytic activity are located in the cytoplasmic side,  including His35, Ser71 and His317. Based on the above biochemical  results  and  membrane  protein  analysis,  we  deduced  a  possible  catalytic mechanism for TxnB11 (Figure 4B). His35 initially accepts  a proton from the catalytic Ser71, thus activating its hydroxyl group.  Concurrently,  Ser71  attacks  a  bound  acetyl-CoA  at  the  thioester  carbonyl,  forming  a  tetrahedral  intermediate  that  collapsed  to  release CoA, resulting in the formation of an acylated enzyme. The  acyl  group  is  subsequently  transferred  from  the  enzyme  to  the  substrate 2. Once 2 is bound to the active site, its hydroxyl group is  activated by a proton transfer to His317. The carbonyl carbon of  the  acylated  Ser71  is  attacked,  forming  a  second  tetrahedral  intermediate that collapsed to yield TXN-A. Considering the low pKa  of cysteine, it may be more active in this reaction. We constructed  an S71C mutant. Contrary to our expectation, the S71C mutant led  to  a  signiﬁcant  decrease  in  the  catalytic  activity  (Figure  4A).  However, it could be explained that the low pKa of cysteine worked  to  its  disadvantage  in  the  resolution  of  the  first  tetrahedral  intermediate, as the reversal of the original nucleophilic attack was  more favorable than that in serine. Sterically, the sulfur of cysteine  also formed longer bonds and had a bulkier van der Waals radius.  So when the serine mutated to cysteine, a larger active cavity was  needed.  Another

So when the serine mutated to cysteine, a larger active cavity was  needed.  Another  important  residue  His100  was  predicted  to  be  located in the transmembrane helices.

Subsequently, the acyl group is transferred from the enzyme to the  acyl  acceptor  (substrate),  yielding  an  acylated  product.  The  identification  of  the  catalytic  residue  Ser71  indicated  that  this  membrane-bound  O-acetyltransferase  might  possess  a  similar  reaction mechanism.  Figure 4    Investigation of the enzymatic reaction mechanism catalyzed by  TxnB11.  A,  Comparing  the  catalytic  activity  of  the  mutant  enzymes  with  wild-type TxnB11. B, A proposed catalytic mechanism for TxnB11.  Generation of acylated analogs of TXN by TxnB11

Considering  the  remarkable  anti-tumor  properties  of  TXN-A,  we  try  to  use  TxnB11  to  generate  novel  acylated  analogs  by  changing  the  acyl  donor.  First,  commercial  propionyl-CoA  and  butyryl-CoA were tested as substrates for TxnB11 (Figure 5A). Only  propionyl-CoA  was  utilized  by  TxnB11,  whereas  longer-chain  length butyryl-CoA was not. When propionyl-CoA was used as the  donor  substrate,  a  new  peak  with  a  longer  retention  time  was  produced (Figure 5B). High resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS)  analysis  showed  the  molecular  weight  of  the  new  compound  matched TXN analog 3 with a propionyl moiety on C4-sugar (Figure  5A and S2). However, more than half of substrate 2 remained non- acylated when propionyl-CoA was used as an acyl donor, while 2  was  completely  acylated  when  acetyl-CoA  supplied.  It  suggests  that TxnB11 prefers short-chain acyl donors (within three carbon  atoms)  because  of  their  small  steric  hindrance.  Moreover,  three  other  short-chain  acyl-CoAs,  which  contain  functional  hydroxyl,  alkynyl, or fluorine (Figure 5A), were synthesized and tested. HPLC  analysis showed that only glycolyl-CoA could be utilized by TxnB11,  and  the  expected  glycolyl  derivative  4  was  generated  (Figure  5A  and 4B). The new derivative was also confirmed by HRMS (Figure  S3).    © 2018 SIOC, CAS, Shanghai, & WILEY-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim  This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.

Due  to  the  low  reaction  efficiency,  we  were  unable  to  accumulate  sufficient  new  trioxacarcin  analogs  3  and  4  for  NMR  analysis.  Despite  that,  considering  the  remarkable  anti-tumor  properties of TXNs, the anti-tumor activity of them was tested. The  large-scale  catalytic  reactions  were  carried  out.  The  resulting  products  3  and  4  were  purified,  and  their  concentrations  were  determined by HPLC using TXN-A (1) as an internal standard. Then,  MTT assay was performed on the human leukemic T cell line Jurkat  to evaluate the anti-tumor activity of 3 and 4, as well as TXN-A (1)  and 2. All four compounds showed potent cytotoxic activity with  nanomolar  half-maximal  inhibitory  concentration  (IC50)  (Figure  6  and Table 1). Compared with TXN-A (1), the O-propionyl derivative  3  showed  slightly  decreased  activity  but  still  persisted  at  an  excellent  level  with  an  IC50  value  of  1.2  nM,  while  the  non- acetylated analog 2 was nearly ten times less, with IC50 of 9.1 nM. According  interactions,[3]  the  C4-sugar  is  to  the  mode  of  TXN-A-DNA  positioned in the minor groove. Therefore, it can be deduced that  the acetoxy moiety in the sugar may provide additional hydrogen  bond and hydrophobic interaction with nucleotide, and thus make  TXNs binding to DNA more tightly. Also, the acyl group with small  steric hindrance is more favorable to this interaction.  Figure 6    In vitro cytotoxicity of TXN-A and its analogs  Table  1    Cytotoxic  activities  of  trioxacarcin  analogs  2,  3  and  4  against  tumor cell Jurkat in comparison to that of TXN-A  We have demonstrated that TxnB11, as a membrane protein,  is  clearly  an  O-acyltransferase,  which  catalyze  the  regioselective  acetylation of the C4-sugar in TXN-A biosynthesis, using acetyl-CoA  as  the  acyl  donor.  Moreover,  a  possible  catalytic  mechanism  involved was described. In vitro assays of TxnB11 with a variety of  acyl donor resulted in the production of two new TXN analogs with  anti-tumor  activity.  Considering  that  there  are  many  similar  membrane-bound  acyltransferases  involved  in  tailoring  steps  of  antibiotics  biosynthesis,  our  characterization  of  TxnB11  not  only  provides  first  insight  into  their  catalytic  mechanism  but  also  presents a new method to create structural diversity and generate  novel anti-tumor compounds.  Bacterial strains, plasmids, biochemicals, and chemicals

E. coli DH5α was used for general gene clone, and E. coli BL21  (DE3) was used for protein expression (Novagen). The expression  vector  pGEX-4T-1  was  originally  from  commercial  sources.  The  acetyl-CoA, propionyl-CoA, and butyryl-CoA were from Sigma, and  all  the  other  common  biochemicals  and  reagents  came  from  standard commercial sources.  Chin. J. The gene txnB11 was PCR amplified and ligated to pGEX-4T-1  following the standard protocol and confirmed by DNA sequencing.  The  resulting  expression  construct  was  transformed  into  E.  coli  BL21 cells for protein expression. The cells were grown at 37 °C in  LB  medium  and  isopropyl-β-D- thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG) for 24 h at 16 °C. Cells were collected  by centrifugation, resuspended in 25 mM Tris-HCl (pH 8.0) and 150  mM NaCl, and disrupted by sonication. Unbroken cells and debris  were removed by centrifugation at 4000 rpm for 10min. Samples  were  collected  from  the  resultant  supernatant  and  were  named  ‘whole-cell  extracts’.  The  supernatant  was  further  treated  by  ultracentrifugation at 100,000 g for 1 h. The cell membranes were  pelleted and solubilized in 25 mM Tris-HCl (pH 8.0), 150 mM NaCl,  1% (w/v) DDM or Triton X-100 for 1.5 h at 4 °C, named ‘membrane  fraction’.  The  resulting  supernatant  was  designated  ‘soluble  fraction’.    Polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis and Western analysis  Protein  analysis  was  carried  out  by  polyacrylamide  gel  electrophoresis in the presence of SDS (Laemmli, 1970). Western  blotting was performed as described (Burnette, 1981), using the kit  ECL plus Western Blotting Detection System (Thermo Pierce). The  anti-GST antibody (Abcam) was used.  In vitro assays of TxnB11

TxnB11 activity assays were performed in 50 µL of 25 mM Tris- HCl (pH 8.0) containing 100 mM substrate 2, 500 mM acyl-CoA, and  TxnB11  from  the  membrane  fraction  (or  the  corresponding  cell  fraction to be tested). After incubation at 30 °C for 1 h, the reaction  products  were  extracted  twice  with  50  mL  of  ethyl  acetate.  The  organic  layer  was  dried  under  vacuum,  the  residue  was  then  redissolved in 50 µL of methanol and analyzed by HPLC.  Preparation of mutant enzymes of TxnB11  The pGEX-4T-1-txnB11 plasmid  was used as the template for  the site-directed mutagenesis. The synthetic oligonucleotides used  for  the  preparation  were  summarized  in  Table  S1.  The  mutated  genes were expressed as the method above.  In general, free acid (10 μmol), PyBOP (9.7 μmol) and K2CO3 (26  μmol)  were  first  dissolved  in  2  mL  of  freshly  distilled  THF  under  argon. Coenzyme A (6.5 μmol) was dissolved in 1 mL of H2O (O2 was  removed by sonication) and added dropwise to the THF solution.  After  stirring  at  room  temperature  for  2  h,  the  reaction  mixture  was  directly  subjected  to  a  Venusil  XBP-C18  semi-preparative  reversed-phase column by HPLC. The fractions containing product  were pooled.    TXN-A  with  known  concentration  was  added  as  an  internal  standard  (IS)  into  samples  containing  compound  3  or  4.  The  samples  were  analyzed  by  HPLC  and  the  peak  area  values  were  measured. Concentration of 3 (or 4) = [Area of 3 (or 4) / Area of  IS]×Concentration of IS.
Determining the concentrations of compound 3 and 4  Bioassays for anti-tumor activities  tested against Jurkat cell.

The  cells  were  cultured  in  RPMI1640  (GIBCO)  that  was  supplemented  with  10%  fetal  bovine  serum  (GIBCO),  and  a  1%  penicillin-streptomycin solution. All of the cell lines were cultured  at 37 °C with 5% CO2 in a humidified atmosphere. The suspension  cells  were  seeded  in  96-well  plates  with  a  density  of  1.6  x  104  cells/well. The compounds were added into each well after short- term  cultivation  at  37  °C.  The  cells  were  treated  with  different  concentrations  of  the  compounds  dissolved  in  DMSO  for  48  h,  using  pure  DMSO  as  a  control.  Cell  viability  was  determined  by  using Cell Counting Kit-8 (CCK-8) (MG6432, MesGen). At the end of  the  compound  treatment  period,  CCK-8  reagent  (10%,  V/V)  was  added, and the plates were incubated at 37 °C for 2 h. Cell viability  in  each  well  was  quantified  by  absorbance  at  450  nm  using  SpectraMax 190 (Molecular Devices Co. Ltd, USA). The percentage  of tumor cell survival was evaluated by the differential of sample  absorbance  at  450  nm  with  or  without  adding  the  anti-tumor  compounds.  The  logarithmic  drug  dosage-tumor  cell  survival  curves were generated, and the IC50 values for each tumor cell line  were  calculated  by  non-linear  regression  analysis  using  the  GraphPad  Prism  5  program  and  the  log  (inhibitor)  vs.  response  (variable  slope)  equation.  To  determine  statistically  credible  IC50  values, at least three independent samples under each condition  were subjected to parallel experiments.  Supporting Information
